## 6. Commits and branches

### 6.1 Branches

- `main` — protected, always green CI
- `feat/<short-name>` — feature work
- `fix/<short-name>` — bugfix
- `refactor/<short-name>` — non-functional change
- `docs/<short-name>` — docs only

### 6.2 Commit messages

Conventional Commits, lowercase scope:

```
feat({{primary_layer_name}}): add the X endpoint
fix({{primary_layer_name}}): handle empty input
refactor({{primary_layer_name}}): extract path validation
docs(architecture): clarify save lifecycle
chore(deps): bump {{example_dep}}
test({{primary_layer_name}}): add round-trip fixture for tables
```

Body wrapped at 72 cols. Reference issues with `Closes #N` or `Refs #N`.

**Do not include "Co-authored-by: Claude" or similar lines.** Commits are authored by the human running you.

{{#if has_user_content_subrepos}}
### 6.3 Two distinct git contexts

There are **two repositories** at play. Don't confuse them.

| | Project repo | User-content repo |
|---|---|---|
| Path | the project root | {{user_content_path}} |
| Contains | source code, this CLAUDE.md, etc. | the user's data |
| Who commits | developers (humans + Claude Code) | {{project_name}} itself, on every save |
| Author | conventional commits | "{{project_name}} <{{project_slug}}@localhost>" |

When a user says "commit your work", they almost always mean the project repo. When they say "save", that goes through {{project_name}}'s save lifecycle and produces a commit in the user-content repo. If unclear, ask.

{{/if}}

